entry.title: [Shopping Service] Make ProductInfo IDs optional
entry.content:
This patch makes both IDs in ProductInfo (offer and cluster) optional

to accommodate for "loose offers" (products that do not have a cluster

ID). The previous assumption was that getting product info from the

shopping service guaranteed a cluster ID, so the existing logic that

used this has also been updated. As of this patch, getting product

info without a cluster ID means no UI or tracking will be available.

This allows us to start sending info with only offer IDs without

breaking existing code paths.

entry.title: Reland "[wayland] Cancel dnd when drag target or dragged window destroyed"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0d9b005cd03fcea1466c8ee5e7f600690a8e380e



See diff against patchset 1 for changes to the original CL.



The original CL was reverted due to flaky failures of the following

test case

WaylandWindowDragControllerTest.

HandleDraggedWindowDestructionAfterMoveLoop



When `move_loop_handler->RunMoveLoop({})` is called it is expected

the server generates a wl_data_device.data_offer and

wl_data_device.enter event. The `drag_target_window_` is set during

a drag when the enter event is received.



The issue was that sometimes ``move_loop_handler->RunMoveLoop({})``

would return before the client had received the offer and enter

events, and sometimes not.



If there is no enter received by the client, the target window is

not set - and deleting the target window will not cancel the drag.

When the events arrive later in this case the offer / enter events

are correctly no-oped as the window does not exist.



The inconsistency of delivered events for the test made it impossible

to test without flakiness. This CL added a call to `wl::SyncDisplay()` and updated expectations for what occurs when the target window is

destroyed.



Original change's description:

> [wayland] Cancel dnd when drag target or dragged window destroyed

>

> This CL updates the WaylandWindowDragController to cancel the dnd

> session client-side when either of the drag target window or the

> dragged window are destroyed.

>

> The dnd session is not cancelled when either the pointer grab or

> origin window are destroyed as this occurrence is already supported

> and defined by the dnd code.

>

> The client terminates the dnd session by calling OnDataSourceFinish()

> which resets the wl_data_source and performs some client-side

> cleanup. The spec indicates that the destruction of the data source

> can be performed to cancel the dnd session.

>

> To handle any possible events sent by the server, but not yet

> received by the client after the dnd session has been cancelled, the

> client will no-op any further dnd events after this has occurred.

>

entry.title: FSA: Exclusively lock swap files
entry.content:
Currently, creating a writable file stream takes a shared lock on the

file, with the idea that multiple writable streams may be associated

with the same file. However, writable streams are expected to be

siloed; creating multiple writers should create a swap file per writer



However, until this CL, the swap file itself was completely unlocked.

Since the swap file lives alongside the file (in the same directory),

sites with access to the parent directory could acquire a file handle

to the swap file directly. This leads to unexpected behavior, such as

the ability to create a writable stream from a swap file.

implementation-defined and it's unclear whether it should even be

possible to acquire a handle to one in the first place.

entry.title: Remove rationalization from FieldTypeFromAutocompleteAttributeValue
entry.content:
Before this CL, FieldTypeFromAutocompleteAttributeValue took the string

value of the autocomplete and the max-length attribute of a form control

to return a HtmlFieldType. It contained heuristics to use the max-length

attribute to generate rationalized HtmlFieldTypes. For example, an

was mapped to an

HtmlFieldType::kCreditCardExp4DigitYear.



The implementation came with two drawbacks:

1) The max-length had to be carried through many function calls.

2) The heuristic cannot be smarter. E.g. an
autocomplete="cc-exp-year" placeholder="YYYY"> could not be mapped to

HtmlFieldType::kCreditCardExp4DigitYear.



By splitting the rationalization from the parsing, we can improve this.



The new rationalization is implemented in https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4493243 but more will follow.

entry.title: Refactoring the race handling to be more comprehensive
entry.content:
This is a refactoring CL to make the race condition handling more

simpler and comprehensive.



As the discussion in the previous CL pointed[1], it's very unlikely in

theory but there could be the case that neither RaceNetworkRequest nor

the fetch handler commits the response. Also, the previous CL introduces

additional properties which manage the race condition between

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient and the owner loader class, which are

complicated.



This CL removes below properties from the class:

- `request_completed_` in RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient

- `is_fetch_handler_response_fallback_` in

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient

- `fetch_response_from_` in ServiceWorkerResourceLoader



Instead, `commit_responsibility_` will be added to

ServiceWorkerResourceLoader. It is the property replacing

`fetch_response_from_`, and literally telling who should commit the

response in the end, RaceNetworkRequest or the fetch handler. When the

fallback or the network error happens, the client can tell the other

side to commit the response. The race can just simply tell who is

responsible to commit the final response, it doesn't have to know the

state of the other side, like the fallback result of the fetch handler,

the network error in RaceNetworkRequest etc.



[1]

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4514795/comment/21231808_966a5777/

entry.title: Enable DPD feature flag on android-arm64-rel
entry.content:
The Dangling pointer detector is controlled by a binary flag and a

runtime flag:



1. The binary flag enable_dangling_raw_ptr_checks:

This flag controls the size of PartitionAlloc refcount, it

increases from 32 bits to 64 bits. It changes the behavior of

PartitionAlloc when a raw_ptr becomes dangling, calling

PartitionAllocs embedder.

This flag requires BackupRefPtr and PartitionAlloc to be enabled to

be effective.

2. The runtime flag PartitionAllocDanglingPtr:

This flag controls the behavior when a dangling pointer is

detected.

By default the dangling pointer is ignored.



This CL activates the dangling pointer feature flag on android-arm64-rel

. This using the binary flag

"enable_dangling_raw_ptr_feature_flags_for_bots" to change the default.



Additional dangling pointer detection documentation available in:

https://crsrc.org/c/docs/dangling_ptr.md

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1j3uw-x9KkdMCdzuWhYr-ryls7-fD3VR3bWwzqeh6NvI/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-41nltFNe_IrzbCQ0jEnugA#heading=h.3m3nqcoku183

entry.title: Reland "[BestEffortServiceWorker] Use RaceNetworkRequest in the fallback case"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 27c0797becaf3cb6ec5daaf3a97335c093328329



Main diff from the original CL:

- Split NetworkRequest_Wins_NotFound test into two small tests

- Fix the bug that network errors are not handled in

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoader::OnComplete.

- Fix the bug that the fetch response is never committed when

1)RaceNetworkRequest result comes first and 2)the fetch handler result

is a fallback, (1) and (2) are both satisfied.





Original change's description:

> [BestEffortServiceWorker] Use RaceNetworkRequest in the fallback case

>

> When the fetch handler result is a fallback,

> ServiceWorkerMainResourceLoader runs the fallback callback,

> ServiceWorkerSubresourceLoader creates another URLLoader, both classes

> dispatches additional network request to get responses.

>

> Currently RaceNetworkRequest doesn't intervene in this fallback process.

> This means the network request is dispatched twice (RaceNetworkRequest +

> fallback), or even three times (+ SW fetch handlers).

>

> This CL changes that behavior, not to dispatch the fallback request when

> RaceNetworkRequest is dispatched. Specifically, when the fetch handler

> response is a fallback, the browser notifies to

> RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient to handle the response and ask to

> complete the commit instead of the fetch handler.

entry.title: HDR Tonemap: Add features for new tonemapping algorithms
entry.content:
Add the feature HlgPqUnifiedTonemap, which will change handling of HLG

to match the behavior outlined in the document linked in

crbug.com/1442884. In particular, it will become the following steps:

- ColorTransformHLGInvOETF

- ColorTransformHLGRefOOTF

- ColorTransformNitsToSdrRelative

- ColorTransformToneMapInRec2020Linear



Add the feature kHlgPqSdrRelative, which will make HLG and PQ content

always use the reference SDR white level of 203 nits. To do this, add

a parameter to ColorTransformNitsToSdrRelative indicating if the

number of its should come from the display settings (which may not be

203 nits on Windows) or if it should use the reference value.



Leave both features disabled. Add lots of tests for both the old and

the new behavior.

entry.title: [3PSP] Allow third-party tokens for DisableThirdPartyStoragePartitioning
entry.content:
We need a way to support OT tokens targeting third-party iframes to

properly bypass storage partitioning. This CL has the iframes examine

all of their parents to see if any frame had the OT enabled rather than

just the top frame. A couple WPTs were added to verify.



This is intended to launch in M115 as an extension to the existing

deprecation trial work, and it not in its own launch process.



Design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1KMyoMXu2u0LEbkNaBGXRdc79dWETkO4sTha3UgE6Gcc/edit?usp=sharing



It's important to note that this differs from the way runtime enabled

features work in the renderer, where a third-party enabling the feature

switches it on in every context that's a child of the context which

injected the token. That's not needed for storage partitioning, so for

now the implementations will differ. The browser process will only be

able to detect if an origin trial is enabled in contexts that are

children of the context in which the token was injected.



We do not want to trust the renderer when it reports scripts/frames

active with 3P origins in the browser process, so we have to defer

validation of the tokens until the browser process knows the origin

to be checked.

entry.title: [NaCL] Eliminate support for PPB_VideoDecoder(Dev) API
entry.content:
In 112, we turned off support for the PPB_VideoDecoder(Dev) API with a

Finch killswitch and enterprise escape hatch policy to re-enable it if

needed through 114. 114 has now branched and there have been no

invocations of the API (per the metric that we added), as well as no

fires caused by turning it off.



This CL eliminates support for the API entirely. In particular, we

do the following:



- Eliminate the Finch killswitch and all code guarded by it

- Eliminate support for the enterprise policy

- Remove all associated tests and metrics



The primary benefit is the elimination of ppb_video_decoder_impl.*,

which is one of the remaining users of the legacy VDA IPC interface.

This elimination (paired with elimination of the other remaining user)

will in turn unblock refactorings to eliminate GLImage and legacy

mailboxes from the codebase.



Note: The API itself is still exposed as of now, but no longer

implemented - resource creation will always fail. We leave removal of

the API entirely for a followup project.



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[NaCl.ResourceCreationImpl.CreateVideoDecoderDev_Invoked]=No longer used

entry.title: [gin] Implement gin::ThreadIsolatedAllocator
entry.content:
We create a PartitionAlloc ThreadIsolated allocator and pass it to v8.



This allocator has to be initialized before we create any threads that use PartitionAlloc:

* on x64 the ThreadIsolated allocator is backed by pkeys

initialization

* On process startup, even read access is blocked to all non-default

pkeys.

* We allow read access in our initializer, but this won't apply to any

previously spawned threads.

entry.title: [text-wrap-pretty] Compute break candidates
entry.content:
This patch makes computing all break candidates (break

opportunities) possible. This is one of requirements for the

score-based line breaking.



To do this:

1. Add `NGLineBreakPoint`, which represents a determined line

break point. This is a superclass of `NGLineBreakCandidate`,

but itself isn't used in this patch yet. Following patches

will use it.

2. Add `NGLineBreakCandidate`, which represents a break

candidate.

3. Add `NGLineBreakCandidateContext`, which computes break

candidates from the results of `NGLineBreaker`.

4. Add `NGLineBreaker::AppendCandidates` which computes all

break candidates in a text `NGInlineItemResult`.



This patch should have no behavior changes, because except a

few minor fixes to `NGLineBreaker` that shouldn't affect

visible behaviors, all changes are called only from unit

tests. Following patches will use this from the actual code.



The logic was tested by following patches by running this code

for all web tests and unit tests. `NGLineBreakCandidateTest`

covers failures found by the tests in addition to basic cases.
